Reasoning: The claim that thigh-length graduated compression stockings (GCS) reduced deep vein thrombosis in patients admitted to hospital who are immobile because of acute stroke is refuted by strong evidence from the CLOTS Trials. Specifically, Paper 23482600, an international multicentre randomized controlled trial (CLOTS Trials 1 and 2) with a large sample size of 5532 immobile stroke patients, found no statistically significant differences in venous thromboembolism events between treatment groups (thigh-length GCS vs. no GCS in Trial 1, and thigh-length vs. below-knee GCS in Trial 2). The study concluded that "No other long-term benefits were apparent" regarding the use of thigh-length stockings. While Paper 49660920, a smaller RCT (sample size 88), showed a numerical difference in DVT incidence between thigh-high (26.8%) and knee-high (38.3%) stockings in hemorrhagic stroke patients, it explicitly stated there was "no significant difference (P = 0.25) observed." The robust findings from the CLOTS trials, with their large sample size and direct relevance to the claim, provide strong evidence against it.
